### As Gaeilge, Le Do Thoil.

When I was studying Irish (no, it is not called "Gaelic") as a lowly undergraduate, it was probably the toughtest thing I've ever learned. I walked into *The Neurobiology of Eating* with a confident swagger, but *Introduction to Modern Irish* had me shaking at the slightest jiggle of the doorknob that warned us that our professor was coming in, likely with the world's most difficult pop quiz in hand. Something my professor was particularly fond of quizzing us on was place names. You would think that would have been easy. Dublin is Dublin. Galway is Galway. Cork is Cork. But no. Nothing is ever easy in Irish. 

It turns out that every place name in Irish has a specific meaning. For example, Dublin derives from *Dubhlinn*, which means "black pool." This is referring to a tidal pool in the gardens of Dublin Castle. It is common, however, for Dublin to also be called *Baile Átha Cliath* (pronounced "ball-yuh aw-huh clee-uh"), which means "town of the hurdled ford." *Dyflin*, which eventually became *Dubhlinn*, was an early Viking settlement, which was neighbored by a Gaelic settlement. Can you guess what the Gaelic settlement was called? That's right. *Baile Átha Cliath*. Hence the name discrepancy.

Another fun example is that Gollum from *The Lord of the Rings* is an Irish place name! Maybe. Who knows, really? A common theory is that Tolkien named Gollum after Poll na gColm (pronounced "Poll nuh Gollum"), a cave in County Clare, Ireland. Poll na gColm means "cave of the rock dove." Where did Bilbo find Gollum? A cave! I will admit that I would love for this to be true.

**I rest my case.**

Unfortunately, when the English colonized Ireland, Irish became less... legal. Even when Irish became legal to speak again and was even made the national language of Ireland, the internalized hatred of Irish lingered. The beauty of place names disappeared. Northern Ireland even had the audacity to rename *Derry* to *Londonderry*. Why? Just why?

### Cad is Ainm Duit?

While many people do not even know that Irish is a language, let alone one still spoken by native speakers in Ireland, many others know how sad it is that Irish has quite literally been wiped off the face of the Earth. On maps, that is. There is an effort, however, to keep the place names alive. In order to cram for my Irish quizzes and exams, I went looking for a map of Irish place names, and I hit the jackpot.

I found [logainm.ie](https://www.logainm.ie/en/) (*logainm* means "placename" in Irish), which is an online Irish resource that finds the Irish place name for any Irish place, locates it on a map, and provides archival evidence of the place name's origins and historical usage.

For example, the place name of the day for December 12, 2020 is An Leac Bhuí in Baile Átha Cliath (Dublin). *An* means "the," *leac* means "flagstone," and Bhuí means "yellow."

### Éire Is Ainm Dom, Go Raibh Maith Agat.

Before I was even vaguely aware of digital humanities, I simply thought this was a great resource for me to use in an attempt to save my grade from the unforgiving cruelty of the place name pop quiz questions. Now, however, I am able to recognize the work that this archival map is doing. Although it is sad to admit, the Irish language is dying. Luckily, there is a revival effort occurring at this very moment, and [logainm.ie](https://www.logainm.ie/en/) is the proof. Archival efforts like this, especially ones this accessible globally, are making links and connections to a forgotten, repressed language. This map is giving Ireland its names back. It is putting Irish back on the map.

I think that in America, we take our place names for granted. Because the United States was ultimately also colonized by the English (surprise, surprise), we also have a very nonchalant attitude towards our place names. In my hometown of Middletown, Delaware, there is a river called the Appoquinimink. My school district was called Appoquinimink. Because this name was "difficult," everyone just shortened it to "Appo," which allowed people to forget that this was a Native American name. Other people lived there first. Middletown had its own place name that we simply did not care to know.

Digital archives and maps have the potential to reveal the "true" face of the Earth. Places named by their native populations. Although digital humanities cannot erase colonization, it can help us remember the people, languages, and cultural artifacts lost to greed.

I would love to see a ditital/archival map that shows pre-colonization place names for all colonized nations. Although it would likely take a large international collaboration with people who are deeply familiar with their nations' histories and languages, I think it would ultimately be worth it in the end.

Imagine if you were named Pádraig by your parents, but all of your teachers in school insisted on calling you Patrick. Did your teachers' ignorance somehow change the name on your birth certificate? No. Treat others the way you want to be treated. Countries included. #vivalalogainm
